because they set out to reject conventionality, but because they aspired to create their own indigenous modernism. While the artists were considered outsiders in their time, their work is now recognized as part of the vital and enduring lineage of American art. Depression hardship ended the Six's ascendancy, but their painterliness, use of color, and deep alliance with the land and the light became a beacon for postwar Northern California modern painters such as Richard Diebenkorn and Wayne Thiebaud. Combining biography and critical analysis, Nancy Boas offers a fitting tribute to the lives and exhilarating painting of the Society of Six.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aColor in artxCalifornia, Northern. 0aColor in art. 0aLandscape paintingy20th centuryxCalifornia, Northern. 0aLandscape paintingzCalifornia, Northerny20th century. 0aLandscape painting, AmericanxCalifornia, Northern. 0aLandscape painting, AmericanzCalifornia, Northern. 4aAmerican art. 4ahistory of art. 4apainting. 4athe arts. 7aART / American / General.2bisacsh1 aEldredge, Charles C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052021055440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052091977840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520919778423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520919778/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY